data.content:
## What breaks in .NET 11

The **sync-over-async opt-in for the Cosmos DB provider is removed**. In .NET 10 you could suppress the warning/error, but in .NET 11 calling synchronous LINQ operators (`ToList()`, `First()`, `Count()`) or `SaveChanges()` on the Cosmos provider throws `InvalidOperationException` unconditionally.

**All four methods break.** The fix is to go fully async:

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

**Key changes:**
- Return types → `Task<T>` / `Task`
- Methods marked `async`, renamed with `Async` suffix
- All EF Core calls use their `*Async` counterparts
- Callers must be updated to `await` these methods (async propagates up the call stack)

Remove any `.EnableSyncOverAsync()` or `CosmosEventId.SyncNotSupported` warning suppression from your `DbContext` configuration — it no longer has any effect.
